#Lyrics
Christ, the life of all the living, Christ, the death of death, our foe, Who, Thyself for me once giving To the darkest shades below; Through Thy suff'rings, death, and merit, I eternal life inherit: Thousand, thousand thanks shall be, Dearest Jesus, unto Thee.  2. Thou, ah Thou, hast taken on Thee Bonds and stripes, a cruel death; Thou didst bear all pain and torment That were due to me, beneath; And the cup of bitter anguish, For my sins Thou once didst languish: Thousand, thousand thanks shall be, Dearest Jesus, unto Thee.  3. Then, for all that wrought my pardon, For the graces Thou dost send, For the sorrow, for the burden, For the sorrows without end; And the love that hath redeemed me, And from death and hell hath freed me: Thousand, thousand thanks shall be, Dearest Jesus, unto Thee.

#Citations and References

Words: Ernst Christoph Homburg, 1659. English trans.: Catherine Winkworth, 1858.
Music: 'Jesu Meines Lebens Leben' Composer unknown; pub. Das grosse Cantional (Darmstadt, 1687). Attribution to Johann Schop (d. 1664) is traditional but not established; Schop's collection "Himmlische Lieder" (1641) preceded the Darmstadt publication.
Setting: Das grosse Cantional (Darmstadt, 1687); tune and text combined in Anhang an das Gothaische Cantional (1776).
copyright: public domain. Homburg (d. 1681); Winkworth (d. 1878); pub. 1659/1687.

